2. What is the percentage of men, women, and children dying from each cause of death? 

childTemp <- migrations %>% select(c(11,12, 22:29)) %>% na.omit(childTemp)
childDrown <- sum(childTemp$Drowning)
childDep <- sum(childTemp$Deprivation)

femDep <- sum(femTemp$Deprivation)
femUnk <- sum(femTemp$Unknown)
femViol <- sum(femTemp$Violence)
femHarsh <- sum(femTemp$`Harsh.Condition`)
femVeh <- sum(femTemp$Vehicle)
femHealth <- sum(femTemp$`Health.issue`)
femOther <- sum(femTemp$`Other`)

df <- data.frame("Children"=c(265,178,37,75,52,98,8,17), "Male"=c(717,552,570,297,241,498,30,128), "Female"=c(289,271,104,106,107,116,13,14))
sumChild = sum(265,178,37,75,52,98,8,17)
sumFem = sum(717,552,570,297,241,498,30,128)
sumMale= sum(289,271,104,106,107,116,13,14)
percent <- data.frame(rep(NA,8))

for(i in 1:8) {
    percent[i,1] <- round((df[i,1]/sumChild *100),2)
}
for(i in 1:8) {
    percent[i,2] <- round((df[i,2]/sumFem *100),2)
}
for(i in 1:8) {
    percent[i,3] <- round((df[i,3]/sumMale *100),2)
}

colnames(percent)[1] <- "Children"
colnames(percent)[2] <- "Male"
colnames(percent)[3] <- "Female"

Percentage <- NA
Causes=c(rep("Drowning") , rep("Deprivation") , rep("Unknown") , rep("Violence"),rep("Harsh Condition") , rep("Vehicle") , rep("Health issue") , rep("Other"))
Gender=c(rep("Children", 8), rep("Male", 8), rep("Female", 8))

for (i in 1:8) {
    Percentage[i] <- percent[i,1]
}
for (i in 1:8) {
    Percentage[i+8] <- percent[i,2]
}
for (i in 1:8) {
    Percentage[i+16] <- percent[i,3]
}
graphData=data.frame(Gender,Causes,Percentage)
ggplot(graphData, aes(y=as.numeric(Percentage), x=Causes, color=Causes, fill=Causes)) + 
    geom_bar(stat="identity") + coord_flip() + ylab("Percentage") +

2. How did the proportion of men, women, and children missing or dead in northern America change year-over-year? 

migrations %>% 
  filter(Region.of.Incident %in% c("US-Mexico Border","Caribbean","Central America")) %>% 
  select(Region.of.Incident,Reported.Year,Number.of.Children,Number.of.Females,Number.of.Males) %>% 
  arrange(Region.of.Incident,Reported.Year) %>% 
  gather(Number.of.Females,Number.of.Males,Number.of.Children,key="Person",value="Number Missing/Dead") %>% 
  mutate(Person=fct_recode(Person,Women="Number.of.Females",
                            Men="Number.of.Males",
                            Children="Number.of.Children"
                            )) %>% 
  group_by(Reported.Year,Region.of.Incident,Person) %>% 
  summarize(number=sum(`Number Missing/Dead`,na.rm=T)) %>% 
  mutate(prop=number/sum(number)) %>% 
  arrange(Region.of.Incident) %>% 
  ggplot() + geom_col(aes(x=Region.of.Incident,y=prop,fill=Person)) + 
  ggtitle("Men, Women, and Children Missing/Dead by Region of Incident") + ylab("Proportion in Region") +  coord_flip() + facet_grid(Reported.Year~.)

1. How has the number of missing migrations in the Mediterranean changed before and after the beginning of the Syrian refugee crisis? 

med <- 
  migrations %>%
  filter(Region.of.Incident == "Mediterranean") %>% 
  mutate(Reported.Date = as.Date.character(Reported.Date, format = "%Y-%m-%d"),
         Reported.Month.Dbl = (lubridate::month(Reported.Date))/12
         ) %>% 
  group_by(Reported.Year, Reported.Month.Dbl) %>% 
  summarise(
    Total.Dead.and.Missing = sum(Total.Dead.and.Missing)
    ) %>% 
  mutate(New.Date=Reported.Year+Reported.Month.Dbl)

med.plot <- 
  ggplot(data = med, mapping = aes(x= New.Date,y = Total.Dead.and.Missing)) + xlab("Year") + ggtitle("Number of Dead and Missing in Mediterranean by Year") + ylab("Number Dead or Missing") + theme_update(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = 6046/3), color = "red")

med.plot



2. What the number of missing and dead by region year-over-year? 

all.regions <- migrations %>%
  mutate(Reported.Date = as.Date.character(Reported.Date, format = ("%Y-%m-%d")),
     Reported.Month.Dbl = (lubridate::month(Reported.Date))/12
     ) %>% 
  group_by(Region.of.Incident,Reported.Year, Reported.Month.Dbl) %>% 
  summarise(
    Total.Dead.and.Missing = sum(Total.Dead.and.Missing)
    ) %>% 
      
  # Arrange Data Chronologically
  mutate(New.Date=Reported.Year+Reported.Month.Dbl) %>% 
filter((New.Date >= 2014) & (New.Date <= 2018))
  
ggplot(data = all.regions, mapping = aes(x= New.Date,y = Total.Dead.and.Missing)) +
  geom_col(aes( fill = Region.of.Incident)) + ggtitle("Number of Dead and Missing by Region per Year") + ylab("Number Dead or Missing") + xlab("Year") + theme_update(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

  select(c("Region.of.Incident", "Number.Dead",

sum$TotalDeprivation = NA

sum$MissingUnknown= NA

sum$TotalViolence <- sum$Number.Dead*sum$Violence

sum$MissingViolence <- sum$Minimum.Estimated.Number.of.Missing*sum$Violence

sum$TotalHarsh = NA
sum$TotalHarsh <- sum$Number.Dead*sum$Harsh.Condition

sum$MissingHarsh= NA
sum$MissingHarsh <- sum$Minimum.Estimated.Number.of.Missing*sum$Harsh.Condition

sum$TotaVehicle = NA
sum$TotalVehicle <- sum$Number.Dead*sum$Vehicle

sum$MissingVehicle = NA
sum$MissingVehicle <- sum$Minimum.Estimated.Number.of.Missing*sum$Vehicle

sum$TotalHealth = NA
sum$TotalHealth <- sum$Number.Dead*sum$Health.issue

sum$MissingHealth  = NA
sum$MissingHealth <- sum$Minimum.Estimated.Number.of.Missing*sum$Health.issue

sum$TotalOther = NA
sum$TotalOther <- sum$Number.Dead*sum$Other

sum$MissingOther  = NA
sum$MissingOther <- sum$Minimum.Estimated.Number.of.Missing*sum$Other

nameTotal <- c("TotalDrowning","TotalDeprivation","TotalUnknown", "TotalViolence", "TotalHarsh", "TotalVehicle", "TotalHealth", "TotalOther")

missTotal <- c(sum(sum$MissingDrowning, na.rm = TRUE),
             sum(sum$MissingDeprivation, na.rm = TRUE),
             sum(sum$MissingUnknown, na.rm = TRUE),
             sum(sum$MissingViolence, na.rm = TRUE),
             sum(sum$MissingHarsh, na.rm = TRUE),
             sum(sum$MissingVehicle, na.rm = TRUE),
            sum(sum$MissingHealth, na.rm = TRUE),
            sum(sum$MissingOther, na.rm = TRUE))

deathTotal <- c(sum(sum$TotalDrowning, na.rm = TRUE),
             sum(sum$TotalDeprivation, na.rm = TRUE),
             sum(sum$TotalUnknown, na.rm = TRUE),
             sum(sum$TotalViolence, na.rm = TRUE),
             sum(sum$TotalHarsh, na.rm = TRUE),
             sum(sum$TotalVehicle, na.rm = TRUE),
            sum(sum$TotalHealth, na.rm = TRUE),
            sum(sum$TotalOther, na.rm = TRUE)) 
         
death <- data.frame(nameTotal, deathTotal, missTotal)
death <- death %>% 
  arrange(desc(deathTotal, missTotal)) 
  
df2 <- melt(death, id.vars = 'nameTotal')

byLocation <- aggregate(cbind(sum$TotalDrowning, 
                sum$TotalDeprivation,
                sum$TotalUnknown,
                sum$TotalHarsh,
                sum$TotalHealth,
                sum$TotalOther,
                sum$TotalVehicle,
                sum$TotalViolence), by=list(Category= sum$Region.of.Incident), FUN=sum, na.rm = T)

DeathbyLocation <- setNames(byLocation, c("Region","Drowning","Deprivation","Unknown",
                                     "Harsh", "Health", "Other",
                                     "Vehicle", "Violence"))

byMissing <- aggregate(cbind(sum$MissingDrowning, 
                sum$MissingDeprivation,
                sum$MissingUnknown,
                sum$MissingHarsh,
                sum$MissingHealth,
                sum$MissingOther,
                sum$MissingVehicle,
                sum$MissingViolence), by=list(Category= sum$Region.of.Incident), FUN=sum, na.rm = T)

DeathByMissing <- setNames(byMissing, c("Region", "Drowning_missing","Deprivation_missing","Unknown_missing",
                                     "Harsh_missing", "Health_missing", "Other_missing",
                                     "Vehicle_missing", "Violence_missing"))


missAndDeath <- inner_join(DeathbyLocation, DeathByMissing, by = 'Region')
missAndDeath <- missAndDeath[ ,order(names(missAndDeath))]
missAndDeath <- select(missAndDeath, Region, everything())


df3 <- missAndDeath %>% 
     select(-c(contains("Unknown"), contains("Other"))) %>%   
     melt(id.vars = 'Region')
df3 <- filter(df3, Region %in% c("US-Mexico Border", "Caribbean", "Central America"))
ggplot(df3, aes(x= Region, y=value, fill=variable)) +
    geom_bar(stat='identity', position='dodge', width = 0.8) +
    ggtitle("Number of Dead and Missing by Region") + ylab("Number Dead or Missing") + theme_update(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Deliverer: Ben Caldwell

1. After Trump’s inaugaration (Jan. 2017), what does the distribution of number of dead by each cause of death look like at the U.S.-Mexico border?


Donald Trump entered office in January of 2017. He was quick to implement a myriad of immigration policies, which has had an observable impact on migration trends, especially along the U.S.-Mexico border.

In terms of border security for the U.S., President Trump ordered the Department of Defense to deploy members of the National Guard to the southern border on April 4, 2018. He thereafter, implemented a series of policies restricting immigration into the United States, particularly from Mexico and Central America by way of the U.S.-Mexico border.

The number of incidents spiked shortly after Donald Trump assumed office at the start of 2017 and started implementing immigration policies. For example, the number of reported incidents jumped by 92 (roughly 11.5%) from the spring of 2018 – when harsher immigration policies went into effect – to the fall of 2018. Furthermore, the region of incident is greatest at the U.S.-Mexico border, accounting for 25% of all incidents globally – 1337 number of incidents.

Additionally, it should be noted that 3005 of all reported incidents occurred after Donald Trump took office. This is roughly 56.3% of all reported incidents, and reporting began in January of 2014.


migrations %>% 
  filter(Region.of.Incident=="US-Mexico Border",post_trump==1) %>% 
  gather(Drowning:Other,key="Cause of Death",value="T/F") %>% 
  group_by(`Cause of Death`) %>% 
  summarize(count=sum(`T/F`)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(count)) %>% 
  ggplot + geom_col(aes(x=`Cause of Death`,y=count, fill=rainbow(8), width=.8)) +
  ylab("Number Dead")+xlab("Season") + theme_update(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))+ ggtitle("Number of Dead by Each Cause of Death") + theme(legend.position = "none")

PARAGRAPH 1 SHOULD DESCRIBE WHAT YOU LEARNED ABOUT YOUR DATA FROM INVESTIGATING THE INITIAL QUESTIONS. DID YOU FIND ANYTHING UNUSUAL IN YOUR DATA? DID ANYTHING SURPRISE YOU? WHICH OF THE INITIAL QUESTIONS WERE HELPFUL IN LEADING YOU TO MORE QUESTIONS?

Paragraph 1

Firstly, and very importantly, we found that drowning was the top cause of death worldwide, regardless of gender. The greatest number of incidents occurred at the U.S.-Mexico border, North Africa, and the Mediterranean. It is important to note that more people were found dead than declared missing in every region around the world for every cause of death excluding drowning. Furthermore, we noticed there were some important periods of time over the course of the five years the data covers. Notably, shortly into 2015, there was a very sharp spike in the number of incidents – both dead and missing – in the Mediterranean. While we can not assume that the following two events are the reason for increased number of incidents, our findings are fitting. We observed an increased number of incidents in the Mediterranean at the start of 2015, and that may be attributed to the Syrian refugee crisis – where many Syrians migrated to Europe by way of the Mediterranean. Also, we observed an increase in the number of incidents at the start of 2018 at the U.S.-Mexico border. Somewhat similarly, this may be attributed policies put in place by U.S. president Donald Trump. The data pulled from incidents at the U.S.-Mexico border is relatively reliable because it has the highest source quality mean, but the data is not as reliable from Central America as its source quality is relatively low. Finally, we found that the majority of missing or dead migrants were men. Women accounted for the second largest percentage of missing migrants aside from children in Central America in 2016 and 2017. Besides these few exceptions, we observed that the data was relatively consistent.

DESCRIBE THE TABLES/FIGURES YOU USED TO EXPLORE ANSWERS TO THESE FOLLOW-UP QUESTIONS? WHAT DID YOU LEARN FROM THE TABLES/FIGURES REGARDING THE FOLLOW-UP QUESTIONS YOU PROPOSED?

Paragraph 2

After combing through our findings from our initial ten questions, we wanted to delve into the dataset even further. We asked ourselves four questions, which piggy-backed off our intial findings. Among those four, we really wanted to explore the possible effects and future reverberations the Syrian refugee crisis would potential have as it pertains to migrant deaths in the Mediterranean through the year 2024. In order to do so we built and used an autoregressive integrated moving average (ARIMA) model to forecast these possible effects. Looking at the ARIMA(1,1,0) model – a differenced first-order autoregressive model – we observed that there is not a ton of projected volatility between 2019 and 2024 in deaths, despite a major spike in deaths shortly into 2016. However, when looking at the other three ARIMA models – especially the damped-trend linear exponential smoothing model – we see there are spikes in the number of deaths at the end of 2019 and smaller spikes every 12 months thereafter. In a nutshell, we found that there may be peaks in migration deaths in the Mediterranean over the next five years that occur every 12 months or so.

We also wanted to dive further into how source quality and cause of death affects the total number of deaths among migrants. We put together a model – regression analysis – that would help us analyze various relationships between some of the variables in our dataset. Particularly, we wished to observe the residuals. With our initial model, we picked variables that might illustrate a relationship to the total number of deaths among migrants globally (response variable). While each model differed in its purpose, we effectively wanted to see which combination of predictors gave us the lowest Mallow’s Cp value – finding the set of predictors that best predict the response variable. With this, we observed that cause of death does have an impact on the total number of deaths among migrations globally.
